<h2>Expert Tips</h2>
<ol class="list-decimal list-inside space-y-4 text-gray-700">
  <li><strong>Match Wine Weight to Steak Cut</strong> - Pair lighter cuts like filet mignon with medium-bodied wines (Côtes du Rhône, Chianti Classico), while heavy marbled steaks like ribeye demand full-bodied powerhouses (Napa Cabernet, Barolo). The fat content in your steak should mirror the wine's tannin structure—high fat needs high tannins to cleanse the palate.</li>

  <li><strong>Temperature Precision for Red Wine with Steak</strong> - Serve your red wine at 60-65°F, not room temperature. This cooler serving temperature enhances the wine's acidity, which cuts through steak's richness more effectively. Use a wine thermometer—too warm and the alcohol overwhelms the meat's flavors, too cold and the tannins become harsh against the protein.</li>

  <li><strong>Decant Based on Steak Preparation Time</strong> - Begin decanting your wine when you start seasoning your steak. Young, tannic wines (under 10 years) need 1-2 hours to soften and integrate, perfectly timing with steak's resting period. Older wines (15+ years) only need 30 minutes to avoid losing delicate aromatics.</li>

  <li><strong>Choose Glassware That Amplifies Steak Pairing</strong> - Use large Burgundy bowls for Pinot Noir with lean steaks to concentrate delicate aromatics, but switch to Bordeaux glasses for Cabernet with fatty cuts—the narrower rim directs wine to the back palate where tannins interact best with meat proteins and fats.</li>

  <li><strong>Factor Cooking Method Into Wine Selection</strong> - Grilled steaks with char marks pair beautifully with smoky wines like Syrah or Châteauneuf-du-Pape, while pan-seared steaks in butter call for wines with bright acidity like Sangiovese. The Maillard reaction's caramelization echoes similar compounds found in oak-aged wines.</li>

  <li><strong>Age Matching Strategy</strong> - Pair aged steaks (dry-aged 21+ days) exclusively with mature wines (10+ years old). Both have developed complex, earthy tertiary flavors that complement each other. Fresh steaks work better with younger, fruit-forward wines where primary flavors won't compete with the meat's funk.</li>

  <li><strong>Seasonal Timing Affects Pairing Success</strong> - Drink bold steak pairings during cooler months when your palate craves richness. Summer steak dinners benefit from slightly chilled Beaujolais or Loire Valley Cabernet Franc—their higher acidity and lower alcohol refresh rather than overwhelm in warm weather.</li>

  <li><strong>Salt Your Steak to Enhance Wine Integration</strong> - Salt your steak 40 minutes before cooking to allow penetration. This draws out moisture and concentrates flavors while making the meat more wine-friendly—the sodium enhances wine's fruit flavors and softens harsh tannins, creating seamless flavor integration between protein and wine.</li>
</ol>

  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
<div class="space-y-6">
  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the difference between pairing wine with ribeye versus filet mignon?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Ribeye's higher fat content and marbling pairs beautifully with bold, tannic reds like Cabernet Sauvignon or Barolo, as the tannins cut through the richness. Filet mignon's leaner, more delicate texture works better with medium-bodied wines like Pinot Noir or Merlot that won't overpower the subtle beef flavors. The key is matching wine intensity to the steak's fat content and flavor profile.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Should I choose different wines based on how my steak is cooked?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Yes, cooking level significantly impacts wine pairing success. Rare to medium-rare steaks retain more delicate flavors that pair well with elegant Burgundy or Sangiovese, while well-done steaks develop more intense, caramelized flavors that can handle robust wines like Petite Sirah or aged Tempranillo. The Maillard reaction in well-cooked steaks creates compounds that complement the toast and spice notes in oak-aged wines.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What wine temperature is best for steak pairings?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Serve red wines slightly cooler than room temperature at 60-65°F (15-18°C) for steak pairings. This temperature allows the wine's tannins to provide structure without being harsh, while preserving the fruit flavors that complement the beef. Overly warm wine can taste flabby and alcoholic against rich steak, while too-cold wine will taste tight and astringent.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Is steak wine pairing good for wine beginners?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Steak and red wine is an excellent pairing for beginners because it's nearly foolproof and demonstrates classic food-wine synergy clearly. The protein and fat in steak soften harsh tannins, making bold wines more approachable, while the wine's acidity cuts through richness to cleanse the palate. Start with crowd-pleasing combinations like ribeye with Cabernet Sauvignon or strip steak with Malbec to build confidence.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the biggest mistake people make when pairing wine with steak?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">The most common mistake is choosing wine based solely on price or prestige rather than considering the preparation and sauce. A $100 Burgundy might be completely overwhelmed by a heavily seasoned steak with chimichurri, while a $20 Côtes du Rhône could be perfect. Always factor in seasonings, marinades, and sauces—they often have more impact on the pairing than the wine's cost.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Can I pair white wine with steak successfully?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Yes, but choose full-bodied, oak-aged whites like Chardonnay or white Rioja for richer cuts, or crisp, high-acid whites like Sancerre for leaner preparations. White wines work particularly well with lighter cooking methods like grilled filet mignon or steak with cream-based sauces. The key is ensuring the wine has enough body and intensity to stand up to the beef without being overpowered.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibend text-wine-700 mb-2">What are good budget-friendly wine options for steak night?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Look for wines from value regions like Languedoc (France), Mendoza Malbec (Argentina), or Washington State Cabernet Sauvignon, which offer excellent steak-pairing potential under $20. Portuguese Douro reds, Spanish Jumilla, and Australian Shiraz blends also provide the tannin structure and bold flavors needed for steak without breaking the bank. Focus on varietals known for good value rather than prestigious appellations.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">How do different steak sauces affect wine pairing choices?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Steak sauces dramatically change pairing dynamics and should guide your wine selection. Béarnaise or hollandaise calls for wines with good acidity like Chablis or Sancerre, while peppercorn sauce pairs beautifully with spicy Syrah or Châteauneuf-du-Pape. Mushroom sauces complement earthy Pinot Noir or Burgundy, and chimichurri's herbaceous qualities work well with Sauvignon Blanc or Cabernet Franc.</p>
